solutions.content:
Two strings are anagrams when their character counts are the same, e.g., "eat" is `{e:1, a:1, t:1}` and "tea" is `{e:1, a:1, t:1}`, so they are in the same group

However the leetcode standard final solution is not ideal, as  you may notice, it stores a count inside a string, so that to present hashkey checking, however in most real world application, we usually create some customized java objects to perform these checking instead of call `toString()`, because `string.equals()` checking is just too slow for real application.

So this is an example we create a 26 characters customized java object and use it as the key to do hashmap lookup. And it's really fast!

```
class Solution {
    class BitKey {
        // should use a set and get
        public final int[] bits;

        public BitKey(int[] bits) {
            this.bits = bits;
        }

        @Override
        public boolean equals(Object o) {
            // If the object is compared with itself then return true  
            if (o == this) {
                return true;
            }

            /* Check if o is an instance of Complex or not
              "null instanceof [type]" also returns false */
            if (!(o instanceof BitKey)) {
                return false;
            }

            // typecast o to Complex so that we can compare data members 
            BitKey c = (BitKey) o;

            if (this.bits.length != c.bits.length) {
                return false;
            } else {
                for (int i = 0; i < this.bits.length; i++) {
                    if (this.bits[i] != c.bits[i]){
                        return false;
                    }
                }
                return true;
            }
        }

        private Integer hash = null;
        @Override
        public int hashCode() {
            if (hash == null) {
                hash = 1;
                for (int i = 0; i < this.bits.length; i++) {
                    hash += (29 << i) * this.bits[i];
                }
            }
            return hash;
        }
    }

    public List<List<String>> groupAnagrams(String[] strs) {
        Map<BitKey, List<String>> map = new HashMap<>();
        for (String s : strs) {
            BitKey count = getCounts(s);

            List<String> data = map.get(count);
            if (data == null) {
                data = new LinkedList<>();
                map.put(count, data);
            }
            data.add(s);
        }

        // convert to result
        return new ArrayList<List<String>>(map.values());

    }

    public BitKey getCounts(String s) {
        int[] counts = new int[26];
        for (int i = 0; i < s.length(); i++) {
            int offset = s.charAt(i) - 'a';
            counts[offset]++;
        }
        BitKey bitKey = new BitKey(counts);
        return bitKey;
    }
}
