Using double as the `HashMap` key is a bad practice. 

But for this problem, as long as we handle the case of gradient `0.0`, it's fine to use `Double`. This is because Double `+0.0` and `-0.0` is treated as  different key.

> Note that in most cases, for two instances of class Double, d1 and d2,
> the value of d1.equals(d2) is true if and only if `d1.doubleValue() == d2.doubleValue()` also has the value true. However,
> there are two exceptions:
> 
> If d1 and d2 both represent Double.NaN, then the equals method returns
> true, even though `Double.NaN==Double.NaN` has the value false. If d1
> represents +0.0 while d2 represents -0.0, or vice versa, the equal
> test has the value false, even though `+0.0==-0.0` has the value true.
> This definition allows hash tables to operate properly.

By adding the following line, it's ok to use `Double` as the key.

    double k =  (p2.y == p1.y) ? 0.0 :((double) (p2.y - p1.y) / (p2.x - p1.x));

