# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
- Two points lie on a line when their slope is equal.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
- To find the maximum number of points that lie on a single line, check lines of all points.
- Starting from point 1 count how many points can lie on the line between point 1 and all others.
- Similarly repeat this process for all points.
- To know if they lie on same line or not, calculate slope and store it in map.
- So for every point maintain map and count of points having differnt slopes.
- Finally return max points that lie on a line. 

# Complexity
- Time complexity: O(N^2)
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity:O(N)
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    int maxPoints(vector<vector<int>>& points) {
        int n=points.size();
        if(n<=2) return n;
        int ans = 0;

        for(auto it1 : points){
            unordered_map<double,int> mp;
            double x1 = it1[0], y1 = it1[1];
            for(auto it2 : points){   
                if(it2 == it1) continue;
                double x2 = it2[0], y2 = it2[1];
                double slope;
                if(x2-x1 == 0){
                    slope = INT_MAX; // slope is infinity for vertical line
                }else{
                    slope = (y2-y1)/(x2-x1);   
                }
                mp[slope]++;
                ans = max(ans,mp[slope]);
            }
        }
        return ans+1; //including point i
    }
};
```

