# Approach
- For each point `points[i]`:
- Initialise a hashmap
- For every subsequent point `points[j]` where `i < j`:
    - Calculate the gradient of the line from `points[i]` to `points[j]`
    - With the gradient as the key in the hashmap increment its value
    - Update the result as the maximum of its previous value and the count for the current gradient
- Return the max count

Since the calculations are always done from one point to every subsequent point only the gradient is required as parallel lines cannot be created.

# Implementation
Originally I started with a Python3 implementation using the `fractions` library as a clean way to avoid floating point aritmetic and implementation of the GCD calculation:
```
from collections import defaultdict
from fractions import Fraction
class Solution:
    def maxPoints(self, points: List[List[int]]) -> int:
        r = 0
        for i in range(len(points)):
            # Count the number of lines with the same gradient
            lines = defaultdict(int)
            for j in range(i+1, len(points)):
                x1,x2 = points[i][0], points[j][0]
                y1,y2 = points[i][1], points[j][1]
                if x1-x2 == 0:
                    line_grad = float("inf")
                else:
                    line_grad = Fraction((y1-y2), (x1-x2))
                lines[line_grad] += 1
                # track the max number of lines with the same gradient
                r = max(r, lines[line_grad])
        return r+1
```

I decided to port this across to C++ and retain the use of a Fraction object as an exercise. I created my own `Fraction` structure with methods for determining the greatest common denominator and for comparison of two Fractions. 

The GCD function is a simple implementation of [Stein's Algorithm](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Binary_GCD_algorithm).

To hash `Fraction` objects for use as a key in a `std::unordered_map` a bitwise XOR of the `int` hash outputs for the numerator and denominator is done.

The logic is the same as the above Python3 code. 

Runtime is around 20-40ms.

# Code
```
struct Fraction {
    int a;
    int b;
    Fraction(int a, int b) {
        if (a==0) {
            this->a = 0;
            this->b = 0;
            return;
        } else if (b==0) {
            this->a = INT_MAX;
            this->b = INT_MAX;
            return;
        }
        int divisor = this->gcd(abs(a),abs(b));
        this->a = a/divisor;
        this->b = b/divisor;
        if ((this->a > 0 && this->b < 0) || (this->a < 0 && this->b < 0)) {
            this->a *= -1;
            this->b *= -1;
        }
    }
    int gcd(int a, int b) {
        // Stein's algorithm
        if (a==0) {
            return b;
        } else if (b==0) {
            return a;
        }
        int i = 0;
        int j = 0;
        while (a&1 == 0) {
            a >>= 1;
            i++;
        }
        while (b&1 == 0) {
            b >>= 1;
            j++;
        }
        int k = min(i,j);
        while (b!=0) {
            if (a > b) {
                swap(a,b);
            }
            b -= a;
            while (b&1 == 0) {
                b >>= 1;
            }
        }
        return a<<k;
    }
    bool operator==(const Fraction &other) const { 
        return (this->a == other.a && this->b == other.b);
    }
};

namespace std {
    template <>
    struct hash<Fraction> {
        std::size_t operator()(const Fraction& k) const {
            using std::size_t;
            using std::hash;
            return hash<int>()(k.a) ^ hash<int>()(k.b);
        }
    };
}

class Solution {
public:
    int maxPoints(vector<vector<int>>& ps) {
        int r = 0;
        unordered_map<Fraction, int> eq_cntr;
        for (int i = 0; i < ps.size(); i++) {
            eq_cntr.clear();
            for (int j = i+1; j < ps.size(); j++) {
                Fraction grad = Fraction(ps[i][1]-ps[j][1], ps[i][0]-ps[j][0]);
                eq_cntr[grad]++;
                r = max(r, eq_cntr[grad]);
            }
        }
        return r+1;
    }
};
```
